Here's the full performance analysis. Given this is a **confirmed hot path** (millions of log entries/min), all findings are elevated accordingly.

---

### Scan Execution Checklist

| Recipe | Hits |
|---|---|
| IndexOf without StringComparison | 0 ✅ |
| Substring | 0 ✅ |
| StartsWith/EndsWith without StringComparison | 0 ✅ |
| Sync-over-async | 0 ✅ |
| ToLower()/ToUpper() | 0 ✅ |
| ToLowerInvariant() (manual check) | 1 |
| Chained Replace (3+) | 0 ✅ |
| `params` | 1 |
| LINQ (Select/Where/Take/Aggregate) | 16 |
| LINQ Any/All | 1 |
| new List< (per-call) | 1 |
| .ToList() | 1 |
| .ToArray() | 1 |
| Enumerable.Reverse (static init) | 1 |
| static readonly Dictionary< | 0 ✅ |
| Unsealed non-static classes | 1 of 1 |
| Sealed classes | 0 |
| Enum.ToString() | 1 |
| virtual methods | 4 |

---

## 🔴 Critical Findings

#### 1. LINQ chains allocate enumerators + delegates on every call (16 instances)

**Impact:** Each `Humanize()` call triggers 5-8 enumerator + delegate allocations from chained LINQ. At millions of calls/min, this dominates GC pressure.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L128, L140, L143, L146, L149, L158, L169, L244, L261-262, L270-272, L284, L304`

**Fix:** Replace LINQ chains with `foreach` loops and manual counting. Examples for the two worst offenders:

`SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan` (L133-150) — 3 LINQ operators + list materialization:
```csharp
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    List<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    var result = new List<string?>(precision);
    int count = 0;
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
    {
        if (count >= precision) break;
        if (!countEmptyUnits && part == null) continue;
        if (countEmptyUnits) count++;
        if (part != null)
        {
            result.Add(part);
            if (!countEmptyUnits) count++;
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

`HumanizeDisplayStrings` (L266-286) — `.Select().Where().ToArray()` chain:
```csharp
private string HumanizeDisplayStrings(IEnumerable<string?> strings, string separator)
{
    var items = new List<string>();
    foreach (var item in strings)
    {
        if (item == null) continue;
        var trimmed = item.Trim();
        if (!string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(trimmed))
            items.Add(trimmed);
    }
    // ... rest unchanged
}
```

#### 2. Enum.ToString() + ToLowerInvariant() — 3 allocations per time unit (1 instance, called N times per Humanize)

**Impact:** `unit.ToString()` uses reflection to allocate a string. `.ToLowerInvariant()` allocates another. Combined with the interpolated string on L176, that's **3 heap allocations per non-zero time unit**, called up to 8× per `Humanize()`.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L175-176`

**Fix:** Cache unit names in a static array:
```csharp
private static readonly string[] s_unitNamesSingular =
[
    "year", "month", "week", "day", "hour", "minute", "second", "millisecond"
];
private static readonly string[] s_unitNamesPlural =
[
